When taking perphenazine while breastfeeding a 1-month-old, there are several safety considerations to discuss with your healthcare provider. 

Research indicates that when a mother takes up to 24 mg of perphenazine daily, only low levels of the medication are found in breast milk. While there is limited long-term data specifically for perphenazine, studies on similar medications in the same class (phenothiazines) have not shown adverse developmental effects when used alone. 

Because this is a Severity 3 warning (moderate risk/monitoring required), you should closely monitor your infant for:
1. Excessive drowsiness or lethargy.
2. Meeting developmental milestones as expected.

Monitoring is especially important if you are taking any other antipsychotic medications at the same time. Please consult with both your psychiatrist and your baby's pediatrician before starting this medication to ensure a coordinated care plan.

