I have found a significant interaction between rosuvastatin and azithromycin monohydrate. 

Azithromycin belongs to a class of antibiotics called Macrolides, while rosuvastatin is an HMG CoA reductase inhibitor (statin). Macrolides can interfere with how your body processes statins by inhibiting the CYP3A4 enzyme. This can lead to higher-than-normal levels of the statin in your blood, which increases the risk of a serious muscle-wasting condition called rhabdomyolysis. Although azithromycin is often considered a lower-risk option within the macrolide class compared to others like erythromycin, the interaction is still flagged at a high severity level (Severity 4).

You should consult your doctor or pharmacist before combining these medications. They may choose to monitor you more closely, adjust your statin dose, or temporarily pause the statin while you finish the antibiotic.

